Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmud Abbas announced on Thursday at the session of the UN General Assembly that he would break all agreements with Israel if the future government of this country tried to meet Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future government of Israel, which will rise, proceed to implement this plan, we will cancel all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all the commitments made," he said.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely," he threatened with pressure Abbas.
"It is our duty to defend all our rights with all possible means - the few consequences - by fully engaging in the application of international law and the fight against terrorism," said the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the former Israeli Prime Minister, was re-elected after the elections of 17 September.
A week before the elections, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include in Israel all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Jaser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements that the United States was patrolling.
84-year-old Abbas also promised to hold general elections on Palestinian soil during the UN General Assembly.
The last one took place in 2006.
"When I return to the country, I will convene local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and all those who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community," declared the Palestinian President solemnly.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, as a permanent observer in the United Nations, to exercise the powers of "full members of the United Nations and all its bodies and institutions."
The Palestinian leader ended his speech with a call to the international community to "force Israel to comply with all the provisions of the United Nations."
The Israeli ambassador, Danny Danon, responded briefly to Abbas' speech saying that the Palestinian leader "prefers to focus in the UN on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel, rather than to fight against the calls for terrorism in the Autonomous Union under its leadership."
However, Danon, as reported by the agencies, did not refer to the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands announced by Netanyahu.
