PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies in the gaming industry, which create innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the 3rd edition of the GameINN programme on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR were the development of a platform for the development of field games based on the AR game engine, which creates a real world map with a user-friendly application; a test and training platform for the verification of practical skills in the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game that simulates the management of real production processes using an innovative virtual world-to-real interaction model using the 4.0 industry concept - is set out in the NCBR message sent on Friday, PAP.
The aim of the GameINN sector programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market by 2023.
According to NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 was PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and the already 300 million PLN support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme are an important boost for further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev," we read in the communication.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective exploitation of the potential we have in Poland.
"The government's incentives for innovative entrepreneurs, such as R & amp; D incentives, skills improvement programmes, IP box and NCBR support programmes drive innovative business activities and allow them to compete more effectively in a highly competitive market," says the Deputy Prime Minister, Minister for Science and Higher Education, Jarosław Gowin, cited in the Communication.
The head of the science department points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also stays in their pockets - three quarters of more entrepreneurs benefited from the R & amp; D reduction in 2018 than a year earlier.
"The deductible costs for R & D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this reduction.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by NCBR in the three editions of GameINN, "stressed the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of NCBR dr inż. Wojciech Kamieniecki recalls that 78 innovative projects have been awarded in the previous two co-financing competitions with a total value of more than PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest in the third competition and the diversity of applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"It is particularly welcome that, as in previous editions, the selected projects include projects for solutions that serve not only entertainment but also industry 4.0," he adds.
In the third GameINN competition for funding of up to PLN 20 million, entrepreneurs, business consortia and business consortia with scientific units could apply.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of funding of approximately PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement was PLN 100 million, but was increased, so 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in co-financing.
Detailed information on the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sector Programme is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the programme in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, including such companies as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Blooper Team and 11 bit studios.
