Majorca counts losses after the bankruptcy of the travel agency Thomas Cook
More than 25,000 foreign tourists will not arrive in October on leave to Majorca as a result of the Thomas Cook travel agency declared bankrupt on Monday.
On Friday, a representative of the Autonomous Government of the Balearic Republic, Marc Pons, among the 25,000 vacationers who will not be able to take their leave in Majorca on October, there are also those who were to travel with companies indirectly associated with Thomas Cook, such as Neckermann.
Pons explained that 80% of the expected vacationers who, due to the bankruptcy of the British company, had to give up their rest in Majorca next month are German citizens and Scandinavian countries.
However, as Pons claims, since Thomas Cook did not direct tourists to the Balearic island during the November-April period, losses to the local economy will be reduced.
He revealed that the Balearic Government had already started negotiations with international operators on "entry into the market of Majorca" after the bankruptcy of the British operator.
According to the estimates of the Diario de Mallorca newspaper, more than 1000 people will lose their jobs due to the tourism crisis in Majorca in October.
About 800 are fired employees of Thomas Cook's Palma office.
Other people will lose their jobs mainly in the hotel sector.
On Monday, together with the announcement of bankruptcy by Thomas Cook in many Majorca hotels, the property owners demanded that the guests pay an extra charge for the accommodation.
This situation has been experienced by several dozen tourists from Poland.
The Balearic Government estimates that by Thursday several dozen hotels in Majorca will cease to operate until at least the end of October in connection with the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook and the companies cooperating with him.
On the other hand, the Friday's Diario de Ibiza daily indicates that the majority of Ibiza hotels that worked with Thomas Cook do not intend to close facilities in the coming weeks.
The newspaper recalls that on this Balearic island, a British bankrupt co-operated with 42 hotels.
On Wednesday, the autonomous Balearic authorities announced that they would ask the Spanish Government to support the region with EUR 100 million to cover the losses caused by the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook's travel agency.
They have revealed that the most affected tourists in this archipelago, some 36 000 people, are located in Majorca.
According to data from the Balearic Government, Thomas Cook owes local tourist companies, mainly hotel operators, some €5 million for the implementation of the July-September 2019 agreements.
