Dakar: The largest mosque in West Africa has been opened
Tens of thousands of people from all over Senegal gathered in the capital on Friday for the inauguration of a huge mosque, considered the largest in West Africa.
Muslims came by bus, car and foot to the Bopp district, where a new mosque could accommodate 30,000 believers.
The building was built by the Moride Brotherhood, which belongs to the ceiling stream of Islam, which dominates Senegal.
Work on the mosque began ten years ago in a wetland area of six hectares, passed on by the government.
The name of the mosque Massalikul Jinan ("Path to Paradise") comes from the title of Sheikh Ahmadou Bamba Mbacke, the 19th century founder of the fraternity, worshipped by followers as a saint.
The mosque is covered with Carrarian marble and has five minarets.
The highest one is 78 meters.
The mosque in the middle will hold 15,000 faithful, and the second is likely to be on the outer splanade.
In the richly finished interiors you can admire the gilded dome, giant chandeliers and decorations handmade by workers from Morocco.
The builders claim that the mosque is the largest in West Africa, but the building still has no comparison to the mosque in other regions.
In Morocco, the Hassan II Mosque in Casablanca can accommodate 105 thousand faithful.
The construction of the mosque, which cost more than EUR 30 million, was financed by private donations.
The government, in addition to the land, funded lighting, sanitation and financed road works worth EUR 10.5 million.
