These trees can disappear completely from Europe.
"42% of the tree species in Europe are at risk," warns the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in the Red Book of European Trees published on Friday.
The list is headed by chestnuts and lambs.
IUCN, an organisation established in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It has been drawn up by experts who have come to the conclusion from the study that 42% of the 454 species of trees found in Europe (and elsewhere in the world) are "highly threatened."
Among the causes of the Red Paper is the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, these trees and shrubs, which occur only or mainly on our continent, are most at risk.
As regards the typical European condition, 58% of the species are at risk from IUCN experts and 15%, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Paper mentions errors in the exploitation of woodland, accelerated urbanisation, excessive logging and subsequent forest fires and changes in the European ecosystem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, moss and lichens is also at great risk.
"The consequences of human activity lead to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and risk the extinction of important and underestimated varieties in Europe, which are the basis of European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet," concluded the report by Luc Bas, who runs the IUCN European office.
