The Senate has decided on key laws
The Senate adopted without amendment the Act on the disclosure of the property of the families of the most important civil servants and of the flights of the most important persons in the country.
52 senators voted in favour of the amendment of the Law on the property of civil servants' families, without amendment, and 14 opposed, with three abstentions.
The senators therefore decided to reject the 12 amendments tabled by Senator PO Sławomir Rybicki during the debate on Wednesday.
According to him, the amendments were to "civilise" and limit the scope of the statement of information on the property situation of own children, children of the spouse, children adapted to cases where children remain in the common household with the person obliged to make a declaration.
The law on the disclosure of family assets of the most important civil servants, which was designed in the Prime Minister's office, was passed by the Sejm on 11 September.
The rules assume that, inter alia, the Prime Minister, Ministers, Members, Senators, Presidents: the Constitutional Court, the Supreme Administrative Court and the Supreme Court, as well as those at the head of other state institutions, will be obliged to include in the declaration of property information on the personal assets of spouses, children and persons living together.
The Senate also did not propose amendments to the Act on the flights of the most important persons in the country.
It regulates which flights have HEAD status and who can be on board government aircraft with the most important people in the country.
The Act also specifies who is responsible for running the Central Flight Register.
55 senators voted for the bill without amendment, 12 against and four abstentions.
According to the bill, every president's flight will be "performed on an official mission."
The President's flights will be accompanied by family members and other persons invited by the President.
On the other hand, the official Prime Minister and Marshal of the Sejm and Senate will be flying only "to carry out tasks directly related to their function."
The Act also specifies the list of persons who can accompany the most important persons in the country during the flight.
