GUS: In Poland, life is getting better
The report on household budgets published by the GUS on Friday shows that as good or rather good a material situation was estimated by as many as 44% of them.
This figure was 37.2% in the previous year, 33.5% in 2016, and previously, since 2009, when the statistical office first examined the subjective assessment of the situation of households, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% in 2009 and more than 20% in 2009.
The best is the material situation of self-employed households.
In this group, over 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the second pole are households of pensioners, where the proportion of such responses was only 18%.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also strongly influenced by the number of children.
The worst is for single parents, of whom 32% declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55% to 60% and 48.8% among childless households.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500 + programme is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst material situation was assessed by single-parent parents and multiple families (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid increase in income, especially from work.
That is not all, however, because the percentage of households who consider their situation to be good is increasing faster than real income.
Moreover, there is no clear link at the level of voivodships between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are made by the inhabitants of Opolskie voivodship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Then there are Lubuskie (47.7%), Silesian (47.6%), Mazovian (47.3%) and Western Pomeranian (47.1%) voivodships.
However, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after taxes and contributions) was less than 94% of the national average and 98% in Lubusk.
The highest income was paid by the people of Mazowiecki (120% of the national average) and Silesian (104%).
On average in Poland the disposable income per person was PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price developments), it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of past years, it's a pretty low score.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
While income growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms and by 4.3% in 2016.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80% and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
