"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring a police officer will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregard of a specific conduct order issued by a police officer is supposed to be a new form of misdemeanor, punishable by a fine, arrest or restriction of liberty.
A change like this is what the police union wants.
The idea came to the Sejm Petitions Commission.
"The case is serious because there are more than half a million criminal cases in Polish courts every year," we read.
The "Rzeczpospolita" has established that the petition which the Independent Police Union is writing to Members on the revision of the Code of Offences has a chance to succeed.
The petitioner proposes a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Offences.
It would read: "He who does not comply with the request or order of a public officer, issued within the limits and under the provisions of the law, is punishable by arrest, fine or limitation of liberty."
"Paragraph 3 of this provision refers to an identical penalty for those who do not follow the instructions, prevent or hinder the performance of their duties," gives the log.
The sociologist Andrzej Kowalski said "Rzeczpospolita" that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if implemented, it can be used in political matters.
"This would be unfavourable in free-movement situations, and instead of mitigating the situation, it would even sharpen it," he adds.
