Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to bankruptcy of Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has failed, its Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
The company, however, has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that they would cancel 105 flights in October due to the bankruptcy problems of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All trips with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but vacationers will be able to receive a refund.
The court in Gandawa also declared three Belgian daughter companies bankrupt: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were supposed to leave with the office by the end of the year.
Even on Monday, spokesperson Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite being declared bankrupt by a British parent company, which has caused concern among employees and customers.
At the time, the office calmed down that the customers who bought the tours in it were going on vacation.
Thomas Cook - the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world - declared bankruptcy last night from Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of bankruptcy was the collapse of the last-chance talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
The creditors demanded that, in addition to the EUR 900 million rescue plan already agreed in August, the company gain an additional 200 million as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnover.
However, the company's problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
