Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for reviews
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion - such an unusual offer was prepared for visitors by German Görlitz.
Actions are designed to help combat the progressive decline in the population of the city.
Görlitz is Germany's most eastern city.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as the Guardian writes, the city is facing significant problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a permanent loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them went west, which resulted in a 25% decline in the city population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54 000 people.
In order to fight depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been received.
Two thirds of them were made up by the inhabitants of the big cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the programme.
"When we applied, we thought the program was going to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel that it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has 7,000 vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times the average in the whole country.
While the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to obtain the opinion of the participants in the programme.
Information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revitalise smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move - what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas for attracting new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a programme of paying promising young professionals to live and work in the city for a year.
Today, such a solution is applied in many places, from the Greek island of Antikyther to Candela in Italy, or in the American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
